Module 10: Git Using Github Desktop#

What is Git?#

Git is a widely-used version control system that facilitates the management of changes to source code over time. Because of this philosophy, it is an essential tool for software development.

It allows multiple developers to collaborate on a project by providing a distributed, non-linear workflow, which enables them to work simultaneously on different parts of a codebase.

Git tracks changes in the form of commits, creating a comprehensive history that helps in understanding the evolution of the project and in identifying when and where changes were made.

It supports branching and merging, allowing developers to experiment with new features or fixes in isolated branches before integrating them into the main project.

Additionally, Git’s robust tools for conflict resolution and its ability to roll back to previous states enhance the reliability and safety of the development process.

Git Installation#

To install Git, simply “Git download” into the browser.

The first link should be the one you want, and it should be named something along the lines of “Downloads - Git”

You will be brought to the Git Downloads page.

From there, you have the choice of downloading the appropriate version of Git, dependent on your operating system.

There are three options: Windows, macOS, and Linux.

Please ensure you download the correct version that’s compatible with your device.

Alternatively, if you know that you already have Git installed and just want to update it to the latest version, you can run the command git clone https://github.com/git/git to obtain the latest development version of Git.

Say for example, I’m using a Windows device. After clicking the “Windows” option, I’m brought to the following page:

After clicking on the bolded Click here to download link, an executable file will get downloaded to my computer.

Once the download finishes, I would click and run that executable.

Click through the instructions prompt, and once that’s done, Git has been sucessfully installed on your device.

What is Version Control, and Why Should You Use It?#

Version control is a system that tracks and manages changes to files over time. It allows multiple people to collaborate on a project, providing tools to coordinate work, track progress, and revert to previous versions if needed.

Version control ensures that changes are recorded systematically, facilitating efficient teamwork and maintaining a complete history of a project’s development.

To version control a project, you typically need two things: (1) a version control system and (2) a repository hosting service.

The version control system is the software that tracks changes, shares your modifications with others, obtains updates from collaborators, and resolves conflicting edits.

The repository hosting service stores a copy of the version-controlled project online (a repository), allowing remote access, issue tracking, bug discussions, and distribution of the final product. There are many options for both of these tools.

In this module, we’ll use Git for version control and GitHub for repository hosting, as they are the most widely used platforms.

Creating a New Repository#

Let’s say I wanted to name this repo “test-repo”, and click the checkbox of “Initialize this repository with a README”.

README#

A README.md file, typically found in the root directory of a Git repository, serves as an introductory document for the project. It provides essential information such as a brief description of the project’s purpose and goals, installation instructions, usage guidelines, and contribution guidelines. The README may also include a brief mention of the project’s licensing terms, often linking to a more detailed LICENSE file. A well-crafted README is crucial as it helps users and contributors understand and utilize the project effectively.

.gitignore#

The .gitignore file is a plain text file used to specify which files and directories Git should ignore. By default, Git tracks all files in a repository, but there are often files that should not be included in version control, such as build artifacts, temporary files, sensitive information, and dependency caches. The .gitignore file lists these files and directories, ensuring they are not tracked by Git. This helps prevent unnecessary clutter in the repository and reduces the risk of exposing sensitive information.

LICENSE#

The LICENSE file contains the legal terms and conditions under which the project’s code can be used, modified, and distributed. Including a LICENSE file is important because it clarifies permissions, outlines limitations and disclaimers to protect the authors from legal liabilities, and provides a clear legal framework that can encourage contributions. There are various open-source licenses to choose from, such as MIT, GPL, and Apache, each with its own terms. The LICENSE file should be placed in the root directory of the repository, making it easily accessible for anyone viewing the project.

GitHub Desktop Interface#

The “Current repository” indicates the repository you are currently working on, in this case, “test-repo.”

The “Current branch” shows which branch of the repository is active, here it is “main.”

The “Publish repository” button allows you to upload the local repository to GitHub, making it available online. This feature is useful for sharing your code with others, collaborating, and using GitHub’s version control features.

Changes and History Tabs#

The Changes and History tabs are crucial for managing and tracking your work within a repository.

The Changes tab displays all the modifications you’ve made to the files in your current branch since your last commit. This includes additions, deletions, and edits. Each file listed in this tab will show specific changes, often highlighted to indicate what was added or removed. This view allows you to review your changes before committing them, ensuring everything is as expected. You can also selectively stage files or individual changes within a file, giving you control over what gets included in your next commit.

The History tab provides a timeline of all the commits that have been made to the repository. It shows a chronological list of commits, including the commit message, author, and date. By clicking on a specific commit, you can see the changes that were made in that commit. This helps in understanding the evolution of the project, identifying when certain features or fixes were introduced, and tracing the origin of any issues. The History tab is essential for tracking the development progress and collaborating with others, as it provides a clear record of what changes were made and why.

Together, the Changes and History tabs help maintain a clear and organized workflow, allowing you to manage and review your work effectively in GitHub Desktop.

Testing Changes#

Let’s open up Microsoft VS Code and navigate to where our newly created folder is located.

As you can see, from the settings in which we made in GitHub Desktop, we also have a README file added on as well.

Now, let’s say I wanted to make some changes to my repository. In particular, I added an index.html file.

Going to GitHub Desktop, we can see the changes of my new file being added.

On the right panel (everything highlighted in green), we can see the actual changes made to the code.

Code that was added is highlighted in green, indicating that it’s new. If there’s pieces of code that’s highlighted red, it means it was removed from the file.

You may also notice a blue checkbox next to index.html. When this box is checked, it means the file will be staged. This means that the user wishes to include this file change in their next commit.

Staging Area#

The staging area in Git is a space where changes are gathered before they are committed to the repository. It allows you to review and selectively include specific modifications, providing control over what is added in the next commit. This intermediate step helps ensure that only intended changes are committed, improving the accuracy and organization of the repository’s history.

Committing Changes to Local Repository#

Committing changes to a local repository in Git involves saving a snapshot of the current state of your project’s files. This process records the changes you have staged, creating a new entry in the project’s history with a unique identifier, a commit message, and metadata about the author and timestamp. Committing helps keep a detailed log of development progress, allowing you to revert to previous states if necessary and collaborate with others effectively by sharing these snapshots.

In the screenshot below, we can see how what it looks like when we wish to commit some changes to our repository. All of this is done in the commit box in the bottom left hand corner of the screen.

The title “Create index.html” was an automatically suggested commit title generated by GitHub Desktop.

After we clicked “Commit to main”, you will notice that the Changes tab is now completely empty.

This means that we have committed these changes, and they now exist as a new entity in the repository history, with its own unique commit hash.

The History Tab#

The History tab provides a comprehensive log of all commits made to the repository. It displays a chronological list of commits, showing details such as commit messages, authors, dates, and the changes introduced in each commit.

By clicking on a specific commit, you can view the differences in the files, which helps in understanding the development progress, identifying when specific changes were made, and tracing the origin of any issues.

When looking at the History tab for our test repository, we can see two commits that were made; one being the creation of the repo (Initial commit), and the other being the creation of the index.html file.

Publishing Repository#

Now, if we wished to publish the repository onto Github, we can do so with the third tab in Github Desktop.

After clicking on that, we can see a pop-up window, giving us prompts on how some specifications in terms of naming.

Pushing Changes from Remote Repository#

If it’s our first time working with a repository, we need to publish it onto GitHub. For all of the subsequent steps afterward, we don’t need to always publish everytime.

Instead, we push our changes to the same remote repository location.

Let’s make another small edit to our index.html file.

We perform similar steps as before, using the Commit section of GitHub Desktop. We click on the blue “Commit to main” button.

Now, when looking at the top bar, instead of “Publish repository”, we have “Push origin”.

This is effectively how we can push changes to our GitHub.

Pulling Changes from a Remote Repository#

Pulling changes from a remote repository involves fetching and integrating updates from a remote Git repository into your local repository. This process ensures that your local branch is up-to-date with the latest modifications made by others. During a pull, Git retrieves the changes from the remote repository and merges them into your current branch, which helps maintain synchronization and collaboration within a team.

If we wanted to pull our changes, we would go to the top Repository tab, then click on “Pull”.
